
[1]offset

   OFF'SET, n. [off and set.]

   1. A shoot; a sprout from the roots of a plant.

   2. In surveying, a perpendicular let fall from the stationary lines to
   the hedge, fence or extremity of an inclosure.

   3. In accounts, a sum, account or value set off against another sum or
   account, as an equivalent.

   [This is also written set-off.]

    OFF'SET, v.t. To set one account against another; to make the account
                   of one party pay the demand of another.
